Barack Obama will be the fourth U.S. president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo, Norway, to spend 26 hours there and be the fourth US president in history to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
The diploma, medal and cheque of $1.4 million will be awarded to him, among others, for his outstanding efforts to strengthen global diplomacy and collaboration among nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will land in the morning in the Norwegian metropolis and have a busy schedule.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time the five members of the Committee who chose him in October from among 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple's schedule then includes an interview with Norway's King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
The visit will peak in the afternoon at a solemn ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth U.S. president to receive it, but only the third to receive the award in the Committee’s own premises.
The White House has informed in advance that Obama will talk about the war in Afghanistan at the award ceremony.
The president does not want to avoid this issue because he is aware that he is receiving this award by being a president who is waging a war in two countries at the moment.
He stepped up the war effort a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, which none of his critics will forget to point out.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a cheque of ten million Swedish kronor (about 1.1 million euros).
He intends to donate it to charities, but he has not yet decided concretely which ones.
His busy schedule then took him and his wife to a banquet that included, in addition to the King and Queen of Norway, the head of government and 250 other guests.
Obama was rather reluctant at this price at first.
He mentioned, for example, that he felt he did not fully deserve it.
He also repeated several times that it is not a price for himself alone, but for all those who defend the same values as him.
As soon as the announcement was made, he said it would be an “invitation to action.”
