United States: Repetition is a Mother of Wisdom
It even becomes comical, the assiduous effort with which Barack Obama, president with the reputation of wise, reproduces the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan issue, which he considered himself to be very simple.
When he finally let his long-awaited doctrine sweat, it turned out that he had copied it on carbon paper since Bush’s Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not content with using in the text even the phrase "as in Iraq" several times, he did not hesitate, moreover, to use the title of Bush's January 2007 speech as the title of his own speech: "A new road forward"
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush’s idea of sending new reinforcements into a civil war-consumed Iraq as “irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its aftermath.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, which emanated from the recommendations of campaign commanders, was the only one possible and likely to be so successful that the newspapers at present do not speak at all of Iraq.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, that being said, objectively speaking, he left his successor in a much more favorable final situation than one could hope for.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
It was again the campaign commanders who called for an increase in the military contingent, including the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even harshly criticized the White House's reluctance despite subordination habits.
He asked for 40,000 men in order to make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months but in the absence of a better option, he swindled at least the 10,000-strong general.
It succeeded in removing the promise of an additional 5,000 from Europe, even though it originally counted on 10,000.
The most problematic part of Obama's strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and to finish this whole process within three years, and Obama's whole doctrine brings more questions than answers.
Many doubt that a half increase will bear the same fruit as the increase in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor the agreements.
The Afghan situation stands out in the exact opposite - no one can be counted on and no treaty is respected.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to day-to-day leadership changes according to what suits them.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain nothing but powder for the eyes behind which will proliferate patriarchal ethnic relations.
It is uniquely complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups in view of the lack of clarity in relations, which are further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a “prompt state to act,” which is the basic goal of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy is perplexing because of his voluntarism.
In the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is currently on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and out-of-reality heart can be persuaded that the small soldiers sent into the turmoil of war for their "prompt return home" will bring there a real miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will regard it as the indirect admission of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is negative.
European politicians do not know and do not want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the enhanced sanctions do not have an effect on the Iranians, the Americans will find themselves faced with the very difficult question of resolving the problem through the use of military force.
It will have to be answered, for example, at a time when, according to Obama, America will come to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will lead to a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only nuisance for Obama is the fact that there are three years until the presidential elections and therefore there is still enough time for him to plan a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
