Pneumococcal vaccination will be free and optional
Vaccination against pneumococci will reverse old habits as early as January.
It will be the first to be free and at the same time optional for families.
There are already voices saying that mandatory vaccination would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of free pneumococcal vaccination are culminating.
The pharmaceutical institute already defines the maximum prices for vaccines that health insurance will pay.
Specialists also see clear in the vaccination process.
A new vaccination.
Free vaccines for children in August.
Since January, children born last year from 2 August can be vaccinated free of charge against pneumococci.
The condition is that they have not yet been vaccinated.
If you started vaccination last year or earlier, you will have to pay for the following vaccinations yourself.
The first dose of vaccine should be given between the 3rd and 5th month of the child.
Last year, a quarter of families voluntarily vaccinated their children against pneumococci.
Yet parents paid 1,600 crowns or more for a dose.
Vaccination of the youngest requires four doses.
Experts estimate that each year health insurance spends 300 to 450,000 crowns on vaccine doses.
They do, however, save on the medical care that unvaccinated children would require.
So far the state has spent about 500,000 crowns a year on all the vaccination of children.
The refunded vaccination was introduced with the "Janota package".
Pneumococci are the cause of inflammation of the middle ear but also serious infections including inflammation of the meninges and blood poisoning.
According to hospital surveys, there are up to 28 deaths of children under the age of 10 caused by pneumococcal infections.
Apart from the Czech Republic, about 40 other countries have introduced reimbursed vaccination.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
There are opinions regarding a possible obligation to vaccinate in the future.
From January, it must be settled by insurance and optional.
For example, Nahlas Rudolf Kalovsk<0xC3><0xBD>, president of the association, said that mandatory vaccination would be more positive.
Its association has long promoted vaccination against pneumococci.
At an international conference in which our association participated, the specialists were not really satisfied with the fact that we have an optional vaccination.
