On the other hand, we are happy to have been able to impose at least this.
I think this is a direction that we must now follow, Kalovsk<0xC3><0xBD> said.
But the Ministry of Health does not want to change the process of vaccination against pneumococci.
We are not considering it at all at the moment, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>.
Optional vaccination has its drawbacks, say doctors.
Hana Cabrnochov<0xC3><0xA1>, president of the Specialized Society of Pediatricians, acknowledges that a vaccination based on volunteering is its flaws.
If all children were vaccinated, a reduction in vaccination renewals could be considered "In the situation where the vaccine costs such a sum I understand the decision making vaccination optional," Cabrnochov<0xC3><0xA1> says however.
Experts predict that by next year, more than 80 percent of new parents will vaccinate their infants.
Vaccination against pneumococci also marks a break in the fact that it is the first vaccination of children that is funded by insurance and not the state.
Cabrnochov<0xC3><0xA1> explains that insurance should free up funds for prevention, thus saving on possible future medical care.
Doctors will have to buy their products themselves.
However, this is related to the concerns of paediatric practitioners, which concern the purchase of vaccines.
