Management revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than ten years, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees has been a reminder of the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of getting employees to adhere to certain "values" from above as it once was, of imposing on consumers products designed by the technicians of the factory.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering markets back in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from the factors of customer preferences returns regularly!
Employee demobilization can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects executives in particular.
This demobilization seriously jeopardizes the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, even more, economic intelligence.
Indeed, EI "requires from all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires from employees a commitment that authoritarian management revenues totally contradict.
This is why we are calling for a management revolution that would put employees at the center of the company’s concerns as well as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion polls – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – incite this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all because I have been able to see that, in the face of a new situation, every structure finally gets, after many detours, to do as a priority... what it has always done.!
Secondly, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
From the major engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the American "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "levers" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr strengthens the leaders in a position of mechanistic governance, unsuitable for today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies requires adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental observation: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a way to realize part of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
At present, only studies from the Reasoning Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to realize their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can monitor, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resources management "in place".
They thus create a favourable ground for the concerted development of robust and effective economic intelligence.
Oslo speech: 'just war' deserves praise from right-wing Obama
The US right-wing welcomed Barack Obama's speech in Oslo on Friday, pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize winner had defended the concept of a "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
The Conservatives, who brocaded the award to Mr. Obama on October 9, applauded the presidential speech this time, as did Sarah Palin, a former vice-presidential candidate in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, Palin, a right-wing Republican, told USA Today, adding that she herself addressed the issue of “sometimes necessary” war in her newly published memoirs.
War is, of course, the last thing in my opinion that Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
We have to stop these terrorists all over there, she said.
Obama, who inherited two wars from his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, worked in Oslo on Thursday to justify the use of force, a way of explaining his decision to send an additional 30,000 troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done "very good work" in Oslo.
I found that the speech was really very good, congratulated the former Speaker of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential statement.
In some ways, I found this speech quite historic, said Mr. Gingrich, interviewed during the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former Elect, considered by some to be a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, said he was delighted to have seen "a left-wing president" remind members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free and could not award a peace prize if the use of force did not exist."
For Michael Gerson, former pen of George W. Bush converted columnist at the Washington Post, Mr. Obama delivered “a very American speech.”
