The first snow can fall
What Wolfgang Braubburger wants is a very harsh winter.
But the head of the road clearing and sanding service (FES) says that it is not to bother citizens.
It is simply so that agents can test the vehicle technique and learn to master them well.
And according to the statologists, it could well be for this weekend.
More than 300 agents and 120 vehicles stand ready to tackle snow and ice.
The EDF follows a very elaborate plan here.
Mr. Brauburger explains that as soon as it starts to snow over the city of Frankfurt and temperatures drop below zero, large sandblasting vehicles run 20 main routes (called A routes).
This includes high traffic streets, main thoroughfares, such as the Neue Weg and the Hanauer Landstraße.
Also included are fire escapes, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloping streets such as Atzelbergstraße.
The EDF officers begin their service at three o'clock in the morning.
If necessary, the 1,040 kilometers of road must be salted with a road surface that adheres well, in a maximum of 3 hours.
This is why the EDF service starts at 3 a.m. "so that the roads are cleared when the daily migration traffic begins".
Where it gets harder is when the snow starts to fall at 7:30 in the morning.
This poses problems, says the head of the clearing and sanding service of the roads "because no motorist is willing to let the salting vehicles pass".
Then, if it does not snow anymore, we take care of the access roads and the service roads - such as the Rat-Beil-Straße.
Secondary lanes and side streets come last.
Mr. Brauburger is well aware that this always leads to a few complaints.
At five o'clock in the morning, the EDF pedestrian team set off to clear priority areas deemed dangerous and crossings.
