The Cradle of Dinosaurs
The Tawa hahae resembled the other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long and 1.50 meters high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with sickle claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and his colleagues report in Thursday’s Science magazine, Tawa hahae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at the time was part of the land of the supercontinent, the Pangaea, and was located towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says the discovery of the Tawa illuminates a new day in the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
Indeed, it informs us about the kinship links, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
In 2006, Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team says they sometimes found a dozen bones in a day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating back to the Triassic.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations have updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories regarding the early evolution of dinosaurs.
Researchers named it Tawa after the Hopi Indian word for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare and are limited to a few fragments of incomplete bones.
Not all paleontology experts share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery particularly spectacular, but he points out that it confirms certain theories regarding the early evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the very first dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, at what time the Saurians divided themselves into three major groups of evolution: the theropods (carnivores) which include the tyrannosaurus and the velociraptor that appeared later and from which descend the birds, the sauropods, quadrupeds with long necks, and those related to them, and the herbivores of which the trinithischians are part.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the first theropods.
This species has an interesting relationship of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found evidence that Tawa hajdae possessed small air sacs in its skull bones, as did birds that are the offspring of theropods.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It appears that in the Tawa hahae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air sacs in its bones.
As the related lineage of the huge sauropods also possessed aerial sacs and a light frame, it may be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive dinosaurs known lived in South America, the researchers concluded that Saurians had appeared there.
As a result, the three great lines of evolution split and spread from South America to the rest of the world, i.e. the entire land area that formed the supercontinent Pangaea.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to him.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor that would have migrated, the researchers say.
Alan Turner of the Museum of Natural History in New York and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says there is an even older species, the Silesaurus, which lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give a wrong view because there are in South America a large number of dinosaur fossils that have been preserved while practically none are found on other continents.
On the other hand, how dinosaurs became the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch remains a mystery to this day.
At the time of the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of modern crocodiles and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread across the planet, favoring the development of many new species while others, related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and the Jurassic.
Such success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or else, the dinosaurs were better suited and so they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such a success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a meteorite favored the blossoming of a group of animals that had also developed during the Triassic and that since that time had been in the shadows: they were mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and there are signatories from all over the world.
