The new “Silicon-valley”
For a long time it had the reputation of a secret city, forbidden to Western visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was, under the Soviet regime, a place of secret armament research, under strict surveillance.
Today with its 216,000 inhabitants 37 km from the center of Moscow, the town has the reputation of being the Soviet "Silicon Valley".
There are important production and research sites in micro- and nanoelectronics.
In September 2008, representatives from Zelenograd established links with Riedberg, the place of the Frankfurt sciences – with the university institutes and companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
There were reciprocal meetings and last Wednesday representatives of Zelenograd and Riedberg ratified a "Protocol of close collaboration".
The signatories were Moscow Deputy Mayor Juri Rosljak and Prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwarz, head of the project section for Frankfurt.
In 2010 representatives of FIZ and SMEs, whose strength is scientific research, will go to Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchanges
