The commune was founded in 1958 as a "planned socialist city" for arms research.
Zelenograd (literal translation “Green City”) takes its name from the wooded hills at the heart of which the research centers are located.
The S21 project: a brake for Stuttgart
The scale of the Stuttgart 21 project cannot be high enough.
For its supporters, it is nothing less than “the new heart of Europe”.
S21 is much more than the burial of a railway station, much more than a colossal construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of Baden-Württemberg into a despairing chaos of construction sites for a decade.
Stuttgart 21 was born from the spirit of the 80s.
The head-to-head stations, with tracks ending in the city, had the reputation at the time of being the relics of the 19th century transport technique that acted as a brake on modern rail traffic because it once took a lot of time to get the locomotives from the rear to the front.
Arrival, short stop, departure – that’s what you have to do.
This is why the main stations must disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart also: a train station, which is located about halfway on the Trans-European Railroad between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava, hence the slogan "heart of Europe".
The realisation of the S21 project will really begin, although the visions of the 80s are no longer compatible with reality for a long time.
Even the most ambitious planners acknowledged that the cost of burying the station in the respective capitals of Hesse and Bavaria was exorbitant.
In fact, the head-to-head stations no longer pose any real entry and exit problems since there are modern trains, reversible with railcars and driver cars at both ends.
However, the construction of Stuttgart 21 is now launched next to the new inter-city line to Ulm.
Regional and municipal policies prevailed.
The railway company is on the side because it is the taxpayer who bears the risks of the largest infrastructure project in the federal republic and not the public enterprise.
From an urban point of view, this project is relatively well justified.
We get an urban space that – if we believe the graphics of the computer-generated planners – will be very green.
For the rail transport system, the S21 is harmful.
The transit station and section expansion are designed for human trafficking to which enormous growth was attributed - and this is typical of the 1980s -.
At the time, there was no competition for cheap flights.
Modern traffic policy should first focus on strengthening freight traffic because transport by rail is much more environmentally friendly than by truck on the road.
But the new layout, with its inclinations, is not suitable for freight trains.
The S21, and this is much more serious, indirectly concerns many other railway projects.
For example, six billion euros will be swallowed up in the Swabian project.
That's the official figure.
Experts believe that ten to fifteen billion are more realistic.
One thing is certain, in the next decade this money will be lacking for other points of junction and congestion in the network.
The Ministry of Transport lists 60 major projects.
One of the most important is the widening of the section through the Rhine Valley by 180 good kilometers.
Since 1987 this line has been built in slow motion.
It would be really urgent to press the mushroom here thoroughly.
But the S21 project has the effect of a brake shoe.
The Rhine Valley route is becoming a bottleneck for international freight traffic in the heart of Europe.
