The Worlds of Dreams
Some see, all awake, images and hear voices that no one else sees or hears.
It is not only in the mentally ill, or under the influence of drugs, that the boundaries between imagination and reality are blurred.
As long as these phenomena occur during sleep, everything is fine.
When we lie in our darkened rooms, we can indulge unhindered in the wildest dreams and fantasies.
However, he who, awake, experiences a dream state, hears and sees things that others do not perceive, soon has the reputation in our Western world of being crazy or drugged, or at least of being an original.
Such images and voices do not appear only in psychic patients or under the effect of drugs.
It is our imagination that is at stake: it is the same neural activity that allows us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, but that sometimes incites the boundaries between dream, madness and reality to merge.
A state of conscious awakening, taking the form of a dream, can present itself in the most diverse forms, in the best case it is called visions, at the worst of madness.
But even if the trigger and the effect are distinguished, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiments of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the second states of shamans, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to very similar processes.
There are hallucinations or delusions when the balance of neurotransmitter substances in the brain – primarily dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine – breaks down and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts occur very often during schizophrenic psychosis.
The Earth's force of attraction no longer has power over the person.
Since antiquity, philosophers and doctors have always looked at the relationship between madness and dreaming.
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of dream-awake; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, in 1861 noted "a great resemblance between madness and dream", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis with all the irregularities, imaginations, delusions and sensory illusions that compose it".
It's autumn 2001 when Henning T transforms into a comic book character.
Her body is in two dimensions with bright colors.
The earthly attraction no longer has power over him, he hovers over the ceiling.
He feels a blow.
Behind him are winged, grimaceous devil creatures with bloody mouths, showing their teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels pain all over his body.
Voices thundering, nasty, screaming, coming out of the walls and the radio.
He can no longer stand those voices that insult and humiliate him.
Henning T. rips two cables from his stereo chain, makes it a loop and attaches it to a hook attached to the ceiling.
He climbs on a baffle and runs the loop around his neck.
He's jumping.
The loop is detached.
Let it teach you, the voices in a choir shout to rip out his eardrum. "Go to a clinic and get yourself treated!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last date of 2 years, the first of almost 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
The diagnosis: schizoaffective psychosis, paranoid, in addition he is manic-depressive, he takes drugs against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
During psychosis I experienced terrible fears and deep despairs.
Illusions are a cruel reality.
Approximately one percent of the population suffers at least once in their lifetime from schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is the most common disease after depression.
In a schizophrenia crisis, those affected can no longer tell the difference between the inner world and the outer world, they find themselves in a state of hyper-excitation, which causes them to suffer from hallucinations, megalomania, relational madness or persecution.
It is very common to hear voices – voices that command, comment, or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also not uncommon.
The person concerned can no longer distinguish between the important and the insignificant, the brain can no longer filter out the disturbing signals, the conscious is drowned under the sensations.
Like the dream, psychosis opens the locks to a tide of ideas and fantasies from the deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, according to Professor Thomas Fuchs, head of the Department of Psychiatry at the Heidelberg University Hospital ( Allgemeine Psychiatrie im Universitätsklinikum).
The schizophrenic is in the center of the situation, all with a meaning centered on him.
At the same time he finds himself in a passive role, he is like in a dream, overcome by events and cannot act on them actively.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, manipulated.
In general they do not have the possibility to adjust reality, illusions are a cruel reality, awakening is excluded.
Experience a hallucination once in your life.
Unlike dreaming, according to Fuchs, "the sensory and spatial structure of reality that is perceived during psychosis is fundamentally preserved."
Delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of experience takes place in a real setting.
Why our brains make these kind of cabriolets, is always a riddle for researchers.
Exceptional situations can cause everyone to momentarily lose perception of reality, according to Fuchs.
But only a small number of people will develop psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determinants.
The researchers assume that the people involved have tiny brain damage.
It is assumed that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development, for example by a viral infection of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But what remains unexplained is the way the neural system anomaly occurs and the fact that it does not manifest itself for many years.
Environmental factors also play a role – stress or a traumatic experience can be a trigger for psychosis, if there is a predisposition.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychoses because they act on neurotransmitters.
When our brain warms up.
What is crazy, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of Lübeck, is that psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and take expensive drugs to get rid of them while others buy expensive drugs to get them.
The pleasant or unpleasant perception of illusions is often just a matter of point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and illusory imagery for the past ten years: last year he published his findings in a book entitled "The Unreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations are part of the concomitant phenomena typical of psychoses but also of an impressive number of many other pathologies.
These include mental disorders such as borderline or depression but also migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease or head trauma.
It is surprising that in some conditions even the brains of healthy people are prone to hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that are normally inhibited.
They take shape when the areas of the brain that process sensory perceptions are hyperactive or not sufficiently restrained; when our brain warms up but also when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition just like a brain injury or psychosis.
But also lack of stimuli, stress, heartbreak or other exceptional mental states.
In recent studies, one-third of participants admit to having experienced hallucination at least once in their life.
In the summer of 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and goes to high school.
A young girl to do normal to tell the truth.
If there weren't the images and the voices.
During the recreation, it happens that a young boy, thin, with long brown hair, addresses him.
When she answers, her comrades look at her, astonished – no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think this shy girl is a lunatic dreamer but Sarah K does not dream, she is sure of it.
She is awake, hears and sees this boy just as she sees and hears the girl sitting next to her on the bench.
She can even sense his presence momentarily.
It's a nice feeling, she finds this young man sympathetic.
Am I crazy? she wonders sometimes.
But she knows well that this young man and the other visions are not real and that they will disappear again.
At night the apparitions are generally frightening.
Visions are often heavy.
When she is in class, she may not be able to take the class because the teacher is just presenting a new student in her eyes and ears while he is invisible to others and the teacher is visibly explaining equations on the board.
At night the apparitions are generally frightening.
When, in the darkness of her room, she waits for sleep that comes too rarely and too late, she often cannot distinguish whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the images she sees, the grimaceous faces or the girl with bloody cuts on her arms and legs are in front of her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, she cries out to these creatures.
She doesn't talk about it to her parents or her friends, they'd think she'd be crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She had her degree last year and she lives with her friend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she got in touch with psychologist Kasten via the internet, she knows she's not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art of despair.
When someone is socially isolated or does not have enough stimulation, the probability is high that they will hallucinate after a certain time.
I suppose the brain not being busy enough, makes sure there is animation.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children when she was a child and often played alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13, that the man she called dad, since she was of the age of thought, was not her real father.
These are the same brain areas that are active for visual and acoustic hallucinations, and for real impressions and noises, so it is very difficult for people like Sarah K to make the difference between illusion and reality.
Hallucinations are also images that form in the brain, which is why they seem so real.”
For Kasten, night dreams are also a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychoses.
Unlike schizophrenics, the mentally healthy person is able to recognize that fantasies are not real images.
That is why Kasten advises his patients to cherish hallucinations as a particular talent.
There is only one step between dreaming and hallucination.
In our too-conscious world, we are sadly quick to take imaginary experiences for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, a professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious disease, painful but which also contains something positive, creative - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the so-called oniroid form of experience, a particular form of dream-awakened consciousness modification.
Oniroid experiences are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the one who lives them and that he cannot differentiate from the dream even when he is awake.
The oniroid state of consciousness manifests itself during trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies such as for patients with polyradiculopathy who are fully aware and experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that damages his life, with his own imaginary world that is dissociated from reality.
It is a state of mental boundary between dreaming and hallucination.
As it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world takes place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, an intense form of means and interpretation, in an intolerable situation in itself, an organizational capacity that is given to us men so as not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in the memory.
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Classen also describes his oniroid experiences in his book "Change of Heart" as a saving action of the soul.
He is 49 years old, at the moment when his conscious leaves for a trip of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed by a transplant; meanwhile, his body is condemned to remain immobile in resuscitation.
Claussen plunges into a world he has created from the ground up, visiting foreign places, traveling back in time. He sees himself as an old man lying in a railway sanatorium, a robot at his bedside watching over his health.
He lives in the Middle Ages among nobles who make blood-based narcotics.
He is kidnapped by a Greek on a motorcycle who takes him to his country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mobster.
He is completely absorbed in this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a completely different state, he writes, describing what he experienced.
Unlike dreams, memories from mental journeys are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
It can even be said that they are much more distinct and more intensive than actual experience.
The intensity of this experience makes the horizon of our other daily experiences burst, according to the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oniroid delusions, psychoses, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of external reality are even in a waking state.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten "can cause a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be quite rewarding.
