75% of working mothers have had professional problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Women's Fertility and Professional Career in Spain", carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers have had limited professional careers due to maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life in a couple and the number of children, whether the woman works or not and the type of job occupied.
Those who have no activity outside the home, work part-time or have an unstable job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier, and have more children.
On the other hand, women in stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are refusing entry into married life and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after settling in as a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. "These data show that women with a stable job needed more time in their lives to get it, which led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised largely influences maternity, but less the date of beginning of joint life, "explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the gap between the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference also persists among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35- to 49-year-old group, those with elementary and higher education were first-time mothers at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average, respectively.
"Another distinction also appears between women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary school get married and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle or higher education reverse this program and prioritize obtaining a stable job as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child,” says Ms. Delgado.
