After rosy days since last spring, during which asset inflation has been the dominant note in the markets, uncertainty arises again, which is not surprising since it is their natural state, in an environment where agents make decisions about a future by nature uncertain.
The remedy used by central banks to stabilize markets has been to monetize debt through the direct purchase of assets and indirectly by giving abundant liquidity at rates close to zero, so that financial institutions buy assets to mobilize.
Central banks have already confirmed that direct asset purchases have been virtually finalized and, without questioning their non-conformist liquidity policy, are starting to put some sand in the wheels, as the ECB did, with their one-year auction next week.
As a result, investors are doubting the ability of the global economy to sustain an economic recovery without heterodox measures and we are witnessing a reversal of risk premium reduction.
Stock market volatility and corporate bond spreads are increasing again, although they remain very far from the paranormal levels they reached at the beginning of the year.
States have been forced to socialize private risk and public debt is again affected.
There is again a flight to quality and the United States, Japan and Germany have been the refuges chosen by investors, causing an increase in differences between the euro area countries and Germany.
